Functional analysis

Here we will perform a differential abundance analysis on the gene orthologue groups in order to quantify the functional capacity of different transcriptomes.

Preprocessing

library(mbtools)
counts <- fread("data/rnaseq/txcounts.csv")
counts[, counts := round(counts)]
counts <- counts[counts > 0]
counts[, sample := tstrsplit(sample, "-")[[3]]]
meta <- fread("data/rnaseq/seq_samples.csv", key = "Sample")
meta[, day := substr(Sample, 4, 6)]
meta[, mouse := substr(Sample, 1, 2)]
meta

Now we will load the SEED annotations for the contigs:

anns <- fread("data/rnaseq/transcripts_seed.csv")
anns

..and join the counts with the annotations:

fncounts <- anns[counts, on = c(query = "transcript"), nomatch = 0]
fncounts <- fncounts[, .(description = description[1], 
                         counts = sum(counts)), 
                     by = c("id", "sample")]
fncounts

We can check if those are more conserved across samples:

cn_per_id <- fncounts[counts > 0, .N, by = id]
ggplot(cn_per_id, aes(x = factor(N))) + geom_bar() + 
  labs(x = "number of samples", y = "shared functions [count]") + theme_bw()

ggsave("figures/function_counts.svg", width = 6, height = 4)

Count matrix

First, we will transform the counts to matrix.

count_mat <- dcast(fncounts, id ~ sample, fill = 0)
Using 'counts' as value column. Use 'value.var' to override
nm <- count_mat[, id]
count_mat[, id := NULL]
count_mat <- as.matrix(count_mat)
rownames(count_mat) <- nm
dim(count_mat)
[1] 4847   17

We will also filter low abundance transcripts from the count matrix.

count_mat <- t(filter_counts(t(count_mat), abundance = 10, presence = 0.25))
nrow(count_mat)
[1] 3254

Let’s visualize the samples in the functional space.

rr pca <- prcomp(log2(mbtools::normalize(t(count_mat)) + 0.5))

converting counts to integer mode

rr explained <- pca\(sdev^2 / sum(pca\)sdev^2) red <- as.data.table(pca\(x) red[, sample := rownames(pca\)x)] red <- meta[red, on = c(Sample = )][day == 29] ggplot(red, aes(x = PC1, y = PC2, color = type)) + geom_point(size = 2) + labs(x = sprintf(1 (%.1f%%), explained[1] * 100), y = sprintf(2 (%.1f%%), explained[2] * 100)) + theme_bw()

rr ggsave(/functional_pca.svg, width = 6, height = 4)

PERMANOVA:

rr library(vegan) counts <- log2(mbtools::normalize(t(count_mat[, meta$day >= 29])) + 0.5)

converting counts to integer mode

rr permanova <- adonis2(counts ~ type, data = meta[meta$day >= 29], method = )

Differential abundance testing

rr library(DESeq2) setkey(meta, Sample) meta <- meta[colnames(count_mat)] days <- c(20, 25, 29) tests <- list() for (d in days) { ds <- DESeqDataSetFromMatrix(count_mat[, meta$day == d], meta[day == d], ~ RIN + type) ds <- DESeq(ds, parallel = TRUE, fitType = ) res <- results(ds) res <- lfcShrink(ds, 3, parallel = TRUE) res$id <- rownames(res) coef_name <- resultsNames(ds)[3] res <- as.data.table(res) res[, day := d] res[, coefficient := coef_name] tests[[d]] <- res } tests <- rbindlist(tests) idmap <- unique(anns[, .(id, description, superpathway, pathway, subpathway)]) setkey(idmap, id) tests <- idmap[tests, on = c()] tests <- tests[order(padj)] fwrite(tests, /responder_tests_seed.csv)

Again below the nominal FDR for the controls.

rr sig_counts <- tests[, .(nsig = sum(padj < 0.05, na.rm = T), n = .N), by = day] sig_counts[, ptr := nsig / n] sig_counts

Also a well-behaved p-value histogram

rr ggplot(tests, aes(x = pvalue)) + geom_histogram(bins = 20) + theme_bw()

To see the large transcriptional shift we can use a volcano plot:

rr day_labels <- sig_counts[order(day), sprintf(%d - %2.1f%%, day, 100 * ptr)] pl <- ggplot(tests, aes(x = log2FoldChange, y = -log10(pvalue), color = factor(day))) + geom_vline(xintercept = 0, lty = ) + geom_point(aes(size = (padj < 0.05 & !is.na(padj))), alpha = 0.5, stroke = 0) + scale_size_discrete(range = c(1, 2)) + guides(size = ) + theme_bw() + theme(legend.position = c(0.15, 0.9), legend.background = element_blank(), legend.key = element_blank(), legend.text = element_text(size = 10)) + labs(x = 2 fold change, color = \) + scale_color_discrete(labels = day_labels)

Using size for a discrete variable is not advised.

rr ggsave(/volcano_functional.png, height = 4, width = 5, dpi = 300) pl

Lets see the most prominent pathways in the significant hits for day 29.

rr sig <- tests[day == 29 & padj < 0.05] sig[, .N, by = ][order(-N)]

Lets have a look at some of the obvious pathways:

library(viridis)

library(scales)

    viridis_pal
library(pheatmap)
pws <- idmap[sig$id, superpathway]
norm_counts <- t(mbtools::normalize(t(count_mat)))[, meta$day == 29]
converting counts to integer mode
keyword <- "Motility"
selected <- norm_counts[sig[grepl(keyword, superpathway), id],]

                                             description], 80)
anns <- data.frame(type = meta[day == 29, type])

names(cols$type) <- levels(anns$type)
rownames(anns) <- meta[day == 29, Sample]
pheatmap(log10(selected + 1), annotation_col = anns, annotation_colors = cols,
         color = viridis(128),
         filename = sprintf("figures/heatmap_%s.pdf", keyword), 
         cellwidth = 10, cellheight = 10, legend_breaks = 0:6)
pheatmap(log10(selected + 1), annotation_col = anns, annotation_colors = cols,
         color = viridis(128), legend_breaks = 0:6)

You can vary the keyword on top to get different submodules.

Pulling out particular function sets

We can also show particular sets of functions. For that let we will write a quick function to build up a merged count data set.

rr tidy_counts <- function(ids, count_matrix, sample_data, function_groups) { cn <- as.data.table(count_matrix[ids, ]) cn$id <- ids cn <- melt(cn, id.vars = , variable.name = , value.name = ) cn <- sample_data[cn, on = ] cn <- function_groups[cn, on = ] cn }

We can now use that to pull out entire subsystems. Let us have a look at the Vancomycin tolerance locus that showed up in the significant results.

rr vanc <- sig[grepl(, subpathway), id] vanc_counts <- tidy_counts(vanc, norm_counts, meta, sig) vanc_counts[, gene := stringr::str_match(description, .+)[, 1]] vanc_counts

We can use that tidy data set to easily visualize a set of genes at once:

pl <- ggplot(vanc_counts, aes(x = gene, y = reads + 0.5, col = type)) +
  geom_jitter(width = 0.2) + scale_y_log10() +
  stat_summary(fun.ymax = mean, fun.ymin = mean, fun.y = mean, 
               geom = "crossbar", width = 0.3) +
  theme_bw() + labs(x = "vancomycin tolerance locus", y = "normalized reads")
ggsave("figures/vancomycin_locus.svg", width = 4.5, height = 3)
pl

acoa_synth <- sig[grepl("CoA synthase", description), id]
as_counts <- tidy_counts(acoa_synth, norm_counts, meta, sig)
pl <- ggplot(as_counts, aes(x = id, y = reads + 0.5, col = type)) +
  geom_jitter(width = 0.2) + scale_y_log10() +
  stat_summary(fun.ymax = mean, fun.ymin = mean, fun.y = mean, 
               geom = "crossbar", width = 0.3) +
  theme_bw() + labs(x = "Acetyl-CoA synthase", y = "normalized reads")
ggsave("figures/acoa_synthase.svg", width = 4, height = 3)
pl
